\begin{proof}
	Let $(i,j)\in J_{p,j}$. Then, $i\leq pq$. Since $p\leq j$, we have $i\leq jq$. Further,  $i\neq p^{\prime}q+1$ for every $1\leq p^{\prime}\leq j$. Hence, we have $(i,j)\in C_{j}\times \{j\}$.\\
	Conversely, let $(i,j)\in C_{j}\times\{j\}$. This implies $i\neq kq+1$ for all $1\leq k\leq j$. Let $p$ be the least positive integer such that $i\leq pq$. Therefore, $i>(p-1)q$. Since $i\neq (p-1)q+1$, we have $(i,j)\in J_{p,j}$.
\end{proof}

